Marsigni. The first part oi the name is that oi the Marsi (see c. 2, 4, and note). T he termination (cp. lieu- digni, c. 40, 1) may denote some kind os eminence in that stock.

Cotini, so read by all recent edd, with Dio, 71. 12, 3; the MSS. text ‘Gotini' being apparently a confusion os this Celtic tribe with the Goths (c. 44, 1). Caesar mentions (6. 24, 2) a Gallie tribe (Volcae Tectosages) on the horder oi the Hercynian forest, but there is no evidence connecting them with this people.

Osi; on these cp. c. 28, 3. Tacitus here speaks os their language as Pan· nonian, which shows them to be an illyrian race, specially related (see l. l.) to the Aravisci. The lllyrian lan· guage, known only through the Alba· nian (cp. c. 1, 1), is considered to have affinities to Greek and Iranian (see Taylor, Origin os Aryans, p. 268).

4. st quod . . . patiuntur, ‘ and the fact tha't they submit to,' co-ordinated with ‘lingua’ as the subject oi ‘arguit'

5. partem i.e. the one (probably the Osi) were tributary to the Sarmatae (the Iazyges noted on c. 1, 1), the other, probably the Cotini, to the Quadi.

6. quo magis pudeat, ie. because they have the material ready to hand which should make arms to win their sreedom, and which was scarce in Ger- many (c. 6, 1). Iron mines in the part of the Hercynian mountains near the Quadi (ie. near Crakow) were known to Ptol. (a. 11, 26).

7. cetorum, ‘but especially’: cp. A. 12. 59, a.

9. ultraquod. The locality oi these tribes would be in Silesia and Poland, between the Oder and Vistula.
